I was curious about how the Guava unsigned integer methods stacked up against those built into JDK 8. Guava was much faster than the JDK in all but the UnsignedLongs.toString() test where the JDK implementation took over 70% less time to execute than the Guava implementation.

In the data below, the columns are Unsigned Type, Performance Percent, JDK Elapsed Nanos, Guava Elapsed Nanos.

```
JDK 8 Wins:
    - Long:ToString:76:16992817:70908659
Google Wins:
    - Byte:Convert:40:242:143
    - Integer:Compare:53:8272155:3811552
    - Integer:Convert:81:3180106:573152
    - Integer:Divide:37:5187307:3250867
    - Integer:ParseString:15:10906276:9224056
    - Integer:ToString:45:18530794:10080654
    - Long:Compare:51:10406576:5019089
    - Long:Divide:82:31011591:5333203
    - Long:ParseString:72:49157371:13578044
```

This is the code I utilized to generate this. The code was executed under Eclipse Mars SR2 running on OS-X with a quad core CPU and 16GB of RAM with little else running to reduce noise. The test was run dozens of times with similar results every time. I used JUnit for ease since this originally started with some sandbox code in a unit test for a class using this functionality. I am currently using Oracle JDK 8u92 as my Java implementation.

